context: All major cities have their distinctive local department stores, which anchored the downtown shopping district until the arrival of the malls in the 1960s. Washington, for example, after 1887 had Woodward & Lothrop and Garfinckel's starting in <a0_0><b4_0>1905<b4_0/><a0_0/>. Garfield's went bankrupt in <a1_0><b5_0>1990<b5_0/><a1_0/>, as did Woodward & Lothrop in 1994. Baltimore had <a2_0><b6_0><b7_0>four<b7_0/><b6_0/><a2_0/> major department stores: Hutzler's was the prestige leader, followed by Hecht's, Hochschild's and Stewart's. They all operated branches in the suburbs, but all closed in the late twentieth century. By <a3_0><b8_0>2015<b8_0/><a3_0/>, most locally owned department stores around the country had been consolidated into larger chains, or had closed down entirely.
